===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|sewen|lang=enm}}, {{term|seowen|lang=enm}}, {{term|sowen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|sīwian}}, {{term/t|ang|sēowian}}, {{term/t|ang|sēowan||to sew, mend, patch, knit together, link, unite}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*siwjaną||to sew}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*sīw-||to sew}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|sew||to sew|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|saie|lang=frr}}, {{term|sei||to sew|lang=frr}}, {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|säie||to sew|lang=stq}}, Danish {{term|sy|lang=da}}, Polish {{term|szyć|lang=pl}}, Russian {{term|шить|lang=ru}}, Swedish {{term|sy|lang=sv}}. Related to {{l|en|seam}}.

====Pronunciation====

Irish: niall horan 
British: Harry,liam.louis,and zayn
Knoll ;)

====Verb====
{{en-verb|sews|sewing|sewed|'''[[sewn]]''' ''or'' '''[[sewed]]''' or (''obsolete'') [[sewen]]}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To use a [[needle]] to pass [[thread]] repeatedly through (pieces of [[fabric]]) in order to join them together.
#: ''Balls were first made of grass or leaves held together by strings, and later of pieces of animal skin '''sewn''' together and stuffed with feathers or hay.''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To use a [[needle]] to pass [[thread]] repeatedly through pieces of [[fabric]] in order to join them together.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To enclose by sewing.
#: ''to '''sew''' money into a bag''

